{"text":"Hi Sken,"},{"text":"\n"},{"text":"\n"},{"text":"Thank you again for your support of the channel.  Given your support and interest in the topic, I'm happy to answer as best as I can.  You bring up a very common problem, specifically in many cases you do not have full state measurement and your C matrix is not the identify matrix.  However, if the system is observable, you can build a state estimator to estimate the state vector (I'm currently working on putting this video together).  If the system is controllable (see my video at "},{"text":" then you can apply the Separation Principle ("},{"text":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_principle)","link":{"linkUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_principle)"}},{"text":" to use the estimated state vector as the input to your full state controller.  I hope this is helpful, please let me know how it goes.  I'll try to keep an eye out for your future comments and be sure to respond but sometimes YouTube comments get lost due to the sheer volume of comments that the channel receives.  I'm much more responsive on Patreon as this is a filtered list of interested parties.  Thanks for watching and for supporting the channel!"}

{"text":"Hi Dave, these are good questions.  A frame and coordinate systems are sometimes used interchangeably. This might be easier to chat about at office hours, please remind me if you'd like to talk at our next meeting, thanks."}
